	
The struggle of the Chinese Auto Industry to move from low-end 
manufacturing to design, engineering and services

Gregory W. Noble
Institute of Social Science
University of Tokyo

February 2008
First draft—not for attribution or quotation without permission

	The animating question for the larger project of which this chapter is a part is how industrialized countries are reacting to the decomposition of production and the emergence of new services (particularly in digitalized services), including responses to the rise of low-wage competitors in manufacturing (especially China) and services (especially India). This chapter focuses on an important case of the reverse question: how does a poor country (in this case, China) with a comparative advantage in labor-intensive manufacturing (here, motor vehicles) react to the same trends in production and services?
	In an ideal-typical formulation, two diametrically-opposed strategic options present themselves. First, the developing country could hail the opportunity to take over cast-off manufacturing operations, especially those with high labor intensities. It would then focus on increasing cost competitiveness and expanding exports, importing more sophisticated and higher value-added parts as necessary. This embrace of static comparative advantage in fact largely describes the approach the Chinese government adopted in the 20 years after it began welcoming investments from Western carmakers in the early 1980s. The Chinese dubbed this 市场换技术--“trading market [access] for technology [transfer],” with technology conceived of as efficient manufacturing and assembly. This approach would seem to be compatible with the interests of multinational corporations, and indeed in 2004 McKinsey consulting proposed that Western automakers operating in China should slough off assembly operations to their Chinese partners so that the Western firms could focus on the more profitable parts of the auto business, including design, engineering, marketing, and services. As the Chinese specialized in low-end manufacturing, the advanced countries faced the prospect of dealing with a deluge of cheap auto imports (as well as the gains from lower prices and a more efficient division of labor), though the rapid development of China’s own market kept most manufacturers focused on domestic sales. 
	An alternative strategy would be to compete directly with Western firms (including automakers from Japan and South Korea) by attempting to move upstream into high valued-added manufacturing (possibly even sloughing off some low-end products to even poorer countries), investing heavily in design and engineering capabilities, and increasing the service content of automobile production, both traditional and digital. This approach, pioneered by Japan and Korea in the 1950s and 1960s, held out the promise of spurring industrialization through the formidable linkages created by auto production, as well as increasing standards of quality and efficiency, and appealing to popular opinion by encouraging the emergence of national champions capable of competing with foreigners in the creation and manufacture of sophisticated products. The textbook dangers of this strategy include creating inefficient infant industries that never grow up, depriving local consumers of access to superior products from abroad, and undermining job creation by encouraging inappropriately capital-intensive products and modes of production. For multinationals, this second strategy threatened to displace some foreign auto production from China, and possibly even to lead to the emergence of low-cost Chinese competitors capable of competing in global markets.
	After a long and contentious debate, in the early years of the new century Chinese policymakers largely endorsed the bolder second strategy, despite its difficulties and dangers, the global trend toward liberalization, and the restrictions placed on industrial and trade policy as a price of China’s entry to the World Trade Organization (WTO) in late 2001. In part, this decision resulted from a desire to capture more value and spur industrialization. Ironically, however, in significant measure it also arose in response to foreign pressures. Chinese officials grew tired of being blamed for giant trade deficits with the United States that resulted in good part from the export of products like Nike shoes or notebook computers that consisted mainly of imported parts and contributed relatively little to the incomes of Chinese workers. The decision also reflected ever-increasing pressure from American and European firms about putative Chinese violations of intellectual property rights (IPRs), and the workings of ever more-efficient global commodity chains that drained value from manufacturing while richly rewarding the foreign firms that designed the final products and controlled the production and distribution chains. If China did not move upstream, policymakers concluded, Chinese firms would always be under the control of foreigners, who would siphon off all the profits, charge ever-more exorbitant licensing fees, and deny China access to critical or sensitive technology. 
	Foreign firms also contributed more directly to the decision not to stick to low-end manufacturing. Foreign automakers proved unwilling to outsource assembly because they were intent on upgrading product quality, preventing the loss of proprietary information, and protecting their global brands. Japanese car companies, in particular, drew a sharp contrast between modular products like personal computers or motorcycles that could be assembled from parts, and integrated products such as cars and airplanes, whose structural integrity, performance and handling characteristics depended on careful coordination and tuning of all sub-systems. Japanese businessmen shook their heads at Chinese car producers that simply copied foreign platforms and bought even crucial assemblies such as engines and transmissions from outside suppliers. 
	The decision to pursue higher value-added and independent designs gained plausibility from the huge size of China’s auto market, which was in the process of passing Japan’s as second-largest in the world, from China’s rapidly expanding supply of young engineers, and from the policy space that remained even after China’s entry into the WTO. China surrendered the right to demand that firms meet minimum levels of local contents and other performance requirements, but it succeeded in retaining a number of de jure policy tools, including tariffs of 25 percent on imports of whole vehicles and an average of 10 percent on parts imports, as well as de facto power to nudge foreign firms in desired directions. With occasional exceptions, such as vehement opposition by European luxury car makers to imposition of whole vehicle tariff rates on imports of car kits, foreign firms and governments proved reluctant to take the government of such a large and competitive market to the WTO.
	Chinese firms, particularly relatively unknown independent firms, have made significant progress in expanding their capabilities in design, engineering, and services, but the process of catch-up is proving to be protracted. Unlike the case of Japanese and Korean automakers, which grew out of protected home enclaves, Chinese auto firms face intense competition in their home market from virtually every major auto and parts producer. Consumer expectations for quality, quiet, efficiency and sophistication are far higher, and product cycles much more rapid, than when Toyota and Hyundai broke into global markets. Moreover, the extraordinarily rapid emergence of the Chinese auto market means that workers, engineers, executives, and government regulators all lack experience, and have to create or reform a whole range of institutions, legal frameworks, and management practices, while trying to accumulate experience in technology and product management.
	As Chinese firms have repeatedly delayed entry to the U.S. market, the thrilling-but-terrifying prospect of ultra-low cost Chinese producers disrupting global markets has given way to cynicism about claims that “the Chinese are coming, the Chinese are coming.” Yet independent Chinese firms continue to make inroads into developing country markets, and even into Eastern and Southern Europe, and Mexico. 
Perhaps the most interesting battle will focus on the development of new propulsion systems such as hybrid and electric vehicles. The Chinese government is intent on cleaning up China’s horribly polluted cities and reducing Chinese consumption of imported fuels. It also sees green vehicles as a new arena of industrial competition in which young Chinese firms may be able to compete on more even terms with foreign masters of conventional technologies such as Toyota or BWM.
	After providing a brief overview of the structure and history of the Chinese auto industry and the policy debates about development strategy, this chapter will examine the efforts of Chinese auto producers to navigate the shoals surrounding the decomposition of production, and expand the range and quality of the services they provide, both as a way of gaining and keeping customers, and as a source of new revenue streams. The automobile industry is a classic example of the increasingly fine division of labor, and the share of value created by outside parts firms has steadily risen, but at the same time, unlike the case with electronics, product integration at the hardware level is critical, and engines and transmissions remain key determinants of product competitiveness. Within manufacturing, the Chinese industry has witnessed two major waves of localization of parts: in the 1980s under the direction of Volkswagen (VW), and around the turn of the century, when the prospect of WTO entry attracted virtually every major global parts producer into the Chinese market.  More recently, Chinese firms have sought to increase their design and engineering skills, but in the short term they rely heavily on Western design and engineering houses. 
