	Dissatisfaction with the watered-down 2004 policy soon sparked renewed debate. The Ministry of Science and Technology [confirm] commissioned a report from a Beijing University professor named Lu Feng who argued vigorously, largely on the basis of interviews with four of the independent auto firms, that direct foreign investment was no substitute for domestic ownership in the vital automobile industry because technology was not tacit, and the capacity to acquire it could come only through learning by doing--assembling someone else’s car was no substitute for designing and engineering one’s own car. Lu warned that without a firm policy to support independent intellectual property rights, the progress of liberalization would not only block auto exports from China, but would eventually marginalize the Chinese partners of the multinationals. 
	Later in 2005 at an auto policy meeting in Guangzhou a fierce debate over the future of the auto industry broke out between Long Yongtu, a former vice-minister of trade and one of the chief negotiators in China’s accession to the WTO, and He Guangyuan, a former head of the machine building ministry and legislator in the Chinese People’s Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC). Long argued that promoting autonomous brands and technology was at best premature, given global trends toward consolidation toward just a few giant automakers, and that ownership did not matter, anyway: as long as a company conducted research and design on Chinese soil, it did not matter who owned it. He Guangyuan countered that the Chinese participants in joint ventures possessed virtually no say over design and engineering and had to go through a lengthy approval process to make even minor changes in foreign models. He endorsed Lu’s contention that genuinely independent intellectual property could only emerge from a genuinely independent brand. Most of the participants sided with He. The debate continued to simmer, as Beijing University Professor Lin Yifu (Justin Lin), later named chief economist of the World Bank, warned that “independent development” could become a costly trapi"/>wdorsed Lu’s contention that genuinely independent intellectual property could only emerge from a genuinely independent brand. Most of the participants sided with He. The debate continued to simmer, as Beijing University Professor Lin Yifu (Justin Lin), later named chief economist of the World Bank, warned that “independent development” could become a costly trapi"/>wdorsed Lu’s contention that genuinely independent intellectual property could only emerge from a genuinely independent brand. Most of the participants sided with He. The debate continued to simmer, as Beijing University Professor Lin Yifu (Justin Lin), later named chief economist of the World Bank, warned that “independent development” could become